name: 7-(trifluoromethyl)-1,2,3,4-tetrahydroquinoline
Reason: The basic unit for comparison will be quinoline, which has a melting point around 23°C. The modifications we need to consider for the target compound are the introduction of a trifluoromethyl group and the saturation of the benzene ring (conversion from quinoline to tetrahydroquinoline). A trifluoromethyl group is electron-withdrawing and also adds to steric bulk, which could raise the melting point. Adding fluorine atoms generally increases the melting point due to the high electronegativity and the increase in intermolecular interactions like dipole-dipole forces. The effect of the trifluoromethyl group might increase the melting point by approximately 20-30°C. The saturation of the benzene ring reduces aromaticity and could slightly lower the melting point, due to reduced pi-pi stacking interactions. We can estimate this effect to be about -5°C. Combining these effects, we would predict an increase relative to quinoline of roughly +15 to +25°C.
